Analyze the following PlantUML use case model and detect if it contains any antipatterns.
Base your analysis solely on the model provided. Do not use any outside knowledge.


PlantUML Model:
@startuml
' Version 1 – contains Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

actor "Citizen" as Citizen
actor "Case Worker" as CaseWorker
actor "Administrator" as Admin

rectangle "Social Benefits Management System" {
  usecase "Submit Benefit Application" as UC1
  usecase "Validate Applicant Identity" as UC2
  usecase "Review Application" as UC3
  usecase "Approve or Deny Benefit" as UC4
  usecase "Generate Benefits Report" as UC5
  usecase "Manage Benefit Programs" as UC6
}

Citizen --> UC1
UC1 ..> UC2 : <<include>>
CaseWorker --> UC3
CaseWorker --> UC4
Admin --> UC5
Admin --> UC6

@enduml


Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Constructs Involved: Submit Benefit Application, Validate Applicant Identity
   Explanation: The use case "Validate Applicant Identity" is an inclusion use case that is included by only one use case ("Submit Benefit Application"). It is not associated with any actor directly, does not include or extend any other use case, is not extended by any other use case, and is not involved in any generalization relationship. "Validate Applicant Identity" represents a sub-step of submitting an application rather than a complete, independently valuable service to any actor. This is a textbook instance of Functional Decomposition via the include relationship — the behavior of submitting an application has been artificially decomposed into a separate inclusion use case that provides no standalone observable result to any user.
